{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489195"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:08:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"617"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/617"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.08,0.05,0.67,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41753"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/617"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26689"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"480"},{"type":"tags","id":"482"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11627"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44695"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41753"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department by ambulance after a fall. He has a recent medical history of giant cell arteritis, with no other significant medical history. His medications include aspirin and prednisolone (40mg daily for the past two months). It is determined that he has a left neck femur fracture, and semi-urgent fixation is planned.  \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate recommendation regarding perioperative steroid management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No adjustment is required","Morning cortisol levels should be measured to determine further steroid management","An ACTH stimulation test should be performed to determine further steroid management","Stress-dose steroids should be arranged perioperatively","The operation should be delayed until a rapid steroid wean can be arranged with Endocrinology input"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe physiological stress response to surgery includes activation of the HPA axis and endogenous steroid production, which among many other actions maintains blood pressure via renal and vascular smooth muscle-mediated mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDetermining whether patients taking exogenous corticosteroids require \u003Cstrong\u003Eperioperative stress dosing\u003C/strong\u003E requires consideration of the likelihood of iatrogenic hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis suppression and subsequent adrenal insufficiency leading to potentially fatal hypotension in the face of surgical stress. Physiological levels of glucocorticoid correspond to approximately 2.5mg/m2/day prednisolone (i.e. ~5mg/day given average adult body surface area), such that exogenous doses equivalent to or beneath this level are unlikely to disturb the HPA axis. Negative feedback within the axis occurs slowly, such that exogenous dosing of any level for less than three weeks is unlikely to cause clinically significant suppression and therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Edo not require any required adjustment in dose.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDoses \u0026gt;20mg/day for over three weeks, however - such as this patient\u0027s - are considered to reliably cause HPA axis suppression and require stress dosing to be arranged with input from the Endocrinology team.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorning cortisol levels\u003C/strong\u003E and/or \u003Cstrong\u003EACTH stimulation tests\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in the setting of intermediate doses (between 5 - 20mg/day of prednisolone), where the HPA axis suppression is less certain and can be determined using these tests. However, they are not commonly performed in this setting, and stress dosing is generally used empirically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esteroid wean\u003C/strong\u003E would take unnecessary time when the option of increasing perioperative steroid dose is available. Management of femoral neck fractures should not be delayed due to increased risk of complications (eg, nonunion, malunion, avascular necrosis) in untreated cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Regimens of \u003E20mg/day prednisolone-equivalent steroid for over three weeks require perioperative stress-dosing"],"references":["Hamrahian A, Roman S, Milan S. The management of the surgical patient taking glucocorticoids. In: UpToDate [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/the-management-of-the-surgical-patient-taking-glucocorticoids","Chilkoti GT, Singh A, Mohta M, Saxena AK. Perioperative \u0022stress dose\u0022 of corticosteroid: Pharmacological and clinical perspective. J Anaesthesiol Clin Pharmacol. 2019;35(2):147-152. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6598572/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26689"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"617"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26689"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-23T08:04:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-13T21:15:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"617"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41753"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/480"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"